<paragraph blockId="11.[151,764,1369,1973]" lastBlockId="11.[809,1422,177,510]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">
Six individuals of this large-eared species were captured in the W1 ravine forest, one in the submontane savannah on the ridge at 
<collectionCode box="[511,556,1539,1565]" country="New Zealand" name="Fossil Catalgoue in the Geology Museum" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">OU</collectionCode>
, and one in a net placed in front of boulders near submontane forest at PF. During the 2002 RAP just one individual was recorded from high elevation at W2 (Fahr and Ebigbo, 2004). The species is known from the Fouta Djallon region (Weber and Fahr, 2007 
<emphasis box="[617,632,1709,1735]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">b</emphasis>
) and from central parts of 
<collectingCountry box="[335,420,1743,1769]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">Guinea</collectingCountry>
(Eisentraut and Knorr, 1957; 
<bibRefCitation author="Konstantinov" box="[151,455,1777,1803]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Konstantinov" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" pagination="129 - 148" refId="ref18332" refString="KONSTANTINOV, O. K., A. I. PEMA, V. V. L ABZIN, and G. V. FARA- FONOVA. 2000. Records of bats from Middle Guinea, with remarks on their natural history. Plecotus et al., 3: 129 - 148." type="journal article" year="2000">
Konstantinov 
<emphasis box="[317,376,1777,1803]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">et al.</emphasis>
, 2000
</bibRefCitation>
). This species is restricted to West Africa where it is known from a number of scattered localities (
<bibRefCitation author="Rosevear" box="[393,584,1845,1871]" firstAuthor="Rosevear" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" refId="ref19462" refString="ROSEVEAR, D. R. 1965. The bats of West Africa. Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London." type="book" year="1965">Rosevear, 1965</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Fahr" box="[601,747,1845,1871]" firstAuthor="Fahr" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" pagination="387 - 389" refId="ref16704" refString="FAHR, J. 2013 b. Hipposideros jonesi Jones's leaf-nosed bat. Pp. 387 - 389, in The mammals of Africa, Volume IV: hedgehogs, shrews and bats (M. HAPPOLD and D. C. D. HAPPOLD, eds.). Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 800 pp." type="book chapter" year="2013" yearSuffix="b">
Fahr, 2013 
<emphasis box="[732,747,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">b</emphasis>
</bibRefCitation>
). The distribution of this bat is closely tied to the availability of caves or disused mine tunnels. At Simandou, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hayman" authorityYear="1947" box="[293,407,1947,1973]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="jonesi">
<emphasis box="[293,407,1947,1973]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">H. jonesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most likely roosts in small caves or crevices in cliffs at the top of the ravine, possibly all the way to forested hilltops such as the Foko site. Whereas all of our captures seemed to be of a grey-brown colour phase, both Eisentraut and Knorr (1957) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Konstantinov" box="[1043,1374,314,340]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Konstantinov" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" pagination="129 - 148" refId="ref18332" refString="KONSTANTINOV, O. K., A. I. PEMA, V. V. L ABZIN, and G. V. FARA- FONOVA. 2000. Records of bats from Middle Guinea, with remarks on their natural history. Plecotus et al., 3: 129 - 148." type="journal article" year="2000">
Konstantinov 
<emphasis box="[1216,1281,314,340]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">et al.</emphasis>
(2000)
</bibRefCitation>
recorded capturing brown-red (‘yellow’), grey-brown (‘grey’) and intermediate colour phases. The female from 
<collectionCode box="[876,918,416,442]" country="New Zealand" name="Fossil Catalgoue in the Geology Museum" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">OU</collectionCode>
captured on 
<date box="[1078,1292,416,442]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" value="2008-02-25">25 February 2008</date>
carried an embryo of 
<quantity box="[936,1018,450,476]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="21.0">21 mm</quantity>
crown-rump length. 
<bibRefCitation author="Konstantinov" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Konstantinov" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" pagination="129 - 148" refId="ref18332" refString="KONSTANTINOV, O. K., A. I. PEMA, V. V. L ABZIN, and G. V. FARA- FONOVA. 2000. Records of bats from Middle Guinea, with remarks on their natural history. Plecotus et al., 3: 129 - 148." type="journal article" year="2000">
Konstantinov 
<emphasis box="[809,868,484,510]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">et al.</emphasis>
(2000)
</bibRefCitation>
recorded one pregnant female in July.
</paragraph>
